    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1907-09-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1907-09-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="27"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d27">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 7661/10.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Chargé <persName type="to">Wilson</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1907-09-13">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 13, 1907</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 135.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of Mr.
                    Beaupré’s dispatch No. 579, of the 3d ultimo, reporting the admission of a
                    shipment of American deviled ham, and expressing the opinion that in future such
                    importations would be attended with no difficulty.</p>
                <p>The department regrets that there has been a renewal of this troublesome
                    question, as shown by your telegram of the 11th [10th] instant.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Alvey A. Adee.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
